<p class="p">The inhibition of the growth of E. coli, K. pneumoniae, S. aureus, P. aeruginosa and E. faecalis was previously reported [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">4</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">7</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R9" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">9</xref>
 </bold>] along with the efficacy against C. albicans [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R9" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">9</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R16" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R17" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">17</xref>
 </bold>] and S. typhimurium [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">4</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R9" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">9</xref>
 </bold>], respectively. In contrast, some studies report the inefficiency of thyme EO against E. coli [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R16" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>
 </bold>,
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R17" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">17</xref>
 </bold>], S. aureus [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R16" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>
 </bold>] and K. pneumoniae [
 <bold class="bold">
  <xref rid="R16" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>
 </bold>].
</p>
